                             @{b}@{u} INTRODUCTION @{ub}@{uu}

     My name is Emilio Perez,I am 20 years old and have been an AMIGA user
     since I was 12.I live in Montevideo,which is the capital of Uruguay,
     a small country in South America.
     I am nor a programmer,neither a musician-just an avid gamesplayer since
     I was 8 years old.I have always dreamed of doing my own game.Then,in
     early 1998 I found this little gem on Internet: "Backbone",by Alastair
     Murray.I was instantly hooked...
     I started way back in my summer holidays in 1998.I was annoyed with
     the lack of a decent platformer on Aminet.I seem to recall some
     okay-ish ones,but the programmers had made them shareware,and asked
     ridiculous fees for the full game.
     The only platformer which I actually loved then was "Alien Fish
     Finger",by David Cusick- one of the few games worth registering on
     Aminet.
     As time passed,though,some good platformers were released,and that
     includes the excellent "Wiz 2",by Steve Eaborn.Anyway,I feel that
     "Charly The Merc" stands on his own:

     This game is a side-viewed platformer featuring 5 standard weapons,
     a secret one and some mission-especific weapons.
     It spans over 3 worlds,each made of various sub-levels.Each world
     is completely different from each other,both in terms of GFX,enemies,
     and even playability.

     I understand that some GFX may look a bit patchy.This is particularly
     true of the Desert levels,which were the first ones I worked on.
     However,as I became more proficient with paint packages,I managed to
     achieve better results.And even some of the desert GFX aren't that
     bad (have a look at mission 1-4,for once).The thing is that the
     later levels feature MUCH better GFX that the first ones.The fact that
     I haven't got a monitor but a TV didn't help a lot,either.

     Besides Backbone,the other software used was Deluxe Paint 4 AGA to
     draw the GFX,and GFXCON to convert the pics you can see at the
     ending from 256 colours to 32.

     Incidentally,when I completed this game I wanted to submit it via
     e-mail to Amiga Format's reader games.I contacted them not one but two
     times-and they never replied!I would like to know what happened...

     Please note that this game features scenes of graphical violence and
     gore that might not be suitable for young children,or even too
     serious people.You have been warned!


    
